Australian, N.Z. Stocks: Kagara, Lynas, Newcrest, St. Barbara

-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 
2011-09-21T06:35:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-21/australian-n-z-stocks-asx-kagara-lynas-corp-st-barbara.html
Australia ’s S&P/ASX 200 Index
gained 0.8 percent to 4,071.80 at the 4:10 p.m. close of trading
in Sydney.  The gauge reversed earlier losses after China’s Conference
Board said its leading index for the world’s second-largest
economy rose 0.6 percent in July, citing a preliminary reading.  New Zealand ’s  NZX 50 Index (NZSE50FG)  advanced 0.6 percent to 3,308.83
at the 5 p.m. close in Wellington.  The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  Gold producers: Gold futures for December delivery gained
1.7 percent in New York yesterday and as much as 0.5 percent
today.  Newcrest Mining Ltd. (NCM)  , Australia’s biggest gold
producer, gained 1.3 percent to A$38.83. St. Barbara Ltd. (SBM
AU) climbed 3.6 percent to A$2.30.        James Hardie Industries SE (JHX)  , a building-materials
supplier that gets almost 70 percent of sales from the U.S.,
surged 5 percent to A$5.85 amid speculation the U.S. Federal
Reserve will today announce new steps to spur the world’s
biggest economy.        Kagara Ltd. (KZL)   slumped 7.4 percent to 50 Australian
cents. The mining company said a strategic review determined
that nickel assets at the Lounge Lizard deposit in  Western
Australia  were “non-core,” and that Goldman Sachs & Partners
Australia Pty has been appointed to advise on “monetizing”
them.       Lynas Corp. (LYC AU), a rare-earths mining producer,
tumbled 12 percent to A$1.28 following declines in prices for
the elements used in electronics and magnets. JPMorgan Chase &
Co. also lowered its rating on Molycorp Inc., the owner of the
world’s largest rare-earth deposit outside  China , citing
declines in rare-earth prices.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shani Raja in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editors responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 